<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; ANGELS; YOUNG'S INJURY PUTS TRADE ON HOLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Angels told first baseman J.T. Snow on Thursday that he may be traded to 
the New York Mets, but negotiations stalled when Met pitcher Anthony Young was 
scratched from a start because of a strained groin muscle. 
</P>
<P>
 Young completed his warm-up throws in the bullpen at Vero Beach, Fla., where 
he was to have pitched against the Dodgers, then felt a twinge in his groin and 
was scratched. That means the Angels will have to delay their plans for at 
least four days. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm disappointed, obviously," Angel General Manager Bill Bavasi said at 
Tempe, Ariz. "We're still very much interested in him, but this is a major 
setback. We want to see him pitch before we do anything." 
</P>
<P>
 If Young had pitched effectively against the Dodgers, Bavasi said the trade 
probably would have been consummated Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
 "If he goes out and pitches four to five innings in his next outing, we'll 
probably realize everything is OK. We'll wait, because we're really not that 
close to doing anything with somebody else." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Pitcher Pete Janicki was optioned to the minor league camp before the Angels' 
10-6 loss to the Chicago Cubs Thursday, but he accomplished in three weeks what 
Manager Buck Rodgers had never envisioned. 
</P>
<P>
 "I didn't think I'd ever seen him throwing like this," Rodgers said. "I'm 
going to have to take back what I said before, because I really didn't think 
he'd ever pitch in the major leagues." 
</P>
<P>
 Janicki returned this spring after suffering a broken right elbow last April 9 
in his first outing. Despite the layoff, Janicki's fastball has been clocked at 
92 m.p.h. He finished his spring with a 0-1 record and a 3.00 ERA.  
</P>
<P>
 "I think I erased all doubts about coming back 100%," Janicki said. "To me, 
it's been very successful." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Pitcher John Farrell cleared waivers Thursday and is expected to accept an 
assignment to triple-A Vancouver. . . . Dan O'Brien, former Angel vice 
president, was hired Thursday as director of baseball operations for the 
Arizona Fall League. BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
