COURT UPHOLDS SEX OFFENDER REGISTRATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The state's 4-year-old law requiring sex offenders to register with the police 
is constitutional, the state Supreme Court ruled Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 In its decision, the court said the statute did not violate the ban against 
applying laws after the fact, nor did it deny sex offenders due process or 
equal protection. 
</P>
<P>
 It rejected the argument that the requirement puts a "badge of infamy" on 
offenders. 
