<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: WESTMINSTER; STUDENTS CHALK IT UP TO SUCCESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thirteen-year-old Paul Marshman plays the oboe in a school band of mostly 
clarinet players. He says he loves being different. He wants to do most things 
his own way. 
</P>
<P>
 But Thursday, Marshman showed he could also be a team player. His idea of a 
rabbit trying to reach for a carrot atop a mountain became the inspiration for 
the winning drawing at McGarvin Intermediate School's sidewalk art competition. 
</P>
<P>
 Five-member teams of seventh- and eighth-graders participated in the art 
contest. They turned the school quadrangle into an impromptu art gallery, 
making chalk drawings on the pavement to portray setting goals, solving 
problems and succeeding in life. 
</P>
<P>
 "We wanted the kids to come together and work as a team," said school 
counselor Lynn Buckley, who organized the art competition as an annual event 
last year as part of a program to teach students how to succeed in life. 
</P>
<P>
 The program, "How to Be Successful in Less Than 10 Minutes a Day," also seeks 
to teach students basic skills to live and work well with other people, Buckley 
said. She said the competition allowed the students to show what they have 
learned in a creative way. 
</P>
<P>
 Their 4-foot-square illustrations had such titles as "Be Confident," "Be a 
Doer" and "Be a Risk Taker," and were associated with spring. 
</P>
<P>
 "It just popped in my mind," Marshman said of his team's drawing, which was 
picked by a panel of seven judges as best among entries from seventh-graders. 
He credited his teammates, however, for turning a "corny" idea to a "pretty 
good" work of art. 
</P>
<P>
 With Marshman on the team were Alex Hogan, Christina Tran, Jacklyn Valdez and 
Orlando Cisneros. The team was selected from the 15 students attending 
beginning band class, according to music teacher Lucy Ewell. 
</P>
<P>
 The math class of Greg Percy topped the eighth-grade competition with a 
drawing of a basketball player shooting over a defender labeled "Fear." 
</P>
<P>
 Julie Linares said she got the idea from a television show, but the catchy 
caption, "If you miss your goal, catch the rebound and try again," was put 
together by her group. Cau Uyen and Donald Yee did most of the drawing. The 
other members of the team were Melissa Watanabe and Scott Monroe. 
</P>
<P>
 Twenty-one teams took part in the competition, according to Buckley, the 
school counselor. The entries were judged on quality of drawing and 
inspirational value, she said. The winners received prizes donated by local 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
 McGarvin Intermediate School is in the Garden Grove Unified School District 
and serves students from Westminster, Garden Grove, Fountain Valley and Santa 
Ana. BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</TEXT>
